{"id":"2112.14002","submitter":"Raymond Centner","authors":"Raymond Centner","title":"Optimal Polynomial Approximants in $L^p$","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CV","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Over the past several years, optimal polynomial approximants (OPAs) have been\nstudied in many different function spaces. In these settings, numerous papers\nhave been devoted to studying the properties of their zeros. In this paper, we\nintroduce the notion of optimal polynomial approximant in the space $L^p$,\n$1\\leq p\\leq\\infty$. We begin our treatment by showing existence and uniqueness\nfor $1<p<\\infty$. For the extreme cases of $p=1$ and $p=\\infty$, we show that\nuniqueness does not necessarily hold. We continue our development by\nelaborating on the special case of $L^2$. Here, we create a test to determine\nwhether or not a given 1st degree OPA is zero-free in $\\overline{\\mathbb{D}}$.\nAfterward, we shed light on an orthogonality condition in $L^p$. This allows us\nto study OPAs in $L^p$ with the additional tools from the $L^2$ setting.\nThroughout this paper, we focus many of our discussions on the zeros of OPAs.\nIn particular, we show that if $1<p<\\infty$, $f\\in H^p$, and $f(0)\\neq 0$, then\nthere exists a disk, centered at the origin, in which all the associated OPAs\nare zero-free. Toward the end of this paper, we use the orthogonality condition\nto compute the coefficients of some OPAs in $L^p$. To inspire further research\nin the general theory, we pose several open questions throughout our\ndiscussions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 28 Dec 2021 05:39:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 10 Jun 2022 13:15:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 30 Jun 2022 19:50:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-04"}
